@JanPaul123 let me know if we should reserve this strictly for the asking of questions. But since I was just reading some of the David Sider book earlier today and it is relevant, here's an excerpt (not a complete answer to the question, just continuing the discussion):

> In sum, as we learn from Kleve, "30 of the Latin papyri are written in Early Roman script and so probably belong to the first century B.C. 11 papyri are written in preclassical capital script and so probably belong to the last part of the first century B.C. (from 31 B.C.). 17 papyri are written in classical capital script and so probably belong to the first century A.D. (until 79 A.D.). The distribution of the scripts indicates that the library in the Papyrus Villa has been an active library, kept up to date to the bitter end."

This is only regarding the Latin scrolls, which are fewer than the Greek (which are represented in the fragments that are part of this dataset). Probably similar information is known about the Greek papyri, but I haven't gotten to that part yet.

@nat 
Ithaca needs more context than this very short fragment can offer. 
I find Perseus under Philologic useful, where you can search on bits of words using wildcards.

@Raf780 
Could it be δεικνύονται instead of δεικνύοντα? 
Then the ημιν suddenly looks a lot neater.

@HannesH asked in DMs why the segments tend to be much wider than they are tall.
The reason for this is that some regions of the scrolls are relatively clean, and in such an area you can easily make many wraps around the center giving a very wide segment. But in order to make it taller you need to run the automatic segmentation and then manually adjust as you go, and in many cases part of the line just turns to mush which makes this very time-consuming and difficult.
This is also something we need better tooling for, since having a whole column from start-to-finish will tell us (or the people who can actually read Greek and then relay that information to us mortals) a lot more, about what sort of text we're dealing with, than only having five-or-so lines of adjacent columns.

@Sostratos Is it not more likely to be εντε etc. though ? 
Now that I look closely there is a segment in that circle .
It makes me think it can only be an ε

It would be ok if the text wasn't fragmentary, but here is a real example from the scrolls. In one of the rows I can clearly see the letters: θηπολλακις, but the letters preceding and afterwards aren't so clear (and remember there are no spaces between words!). πολλάκις is a clear enough word (many times), but, is it:
1. -θη πολλάκις  (the -θη being the ending of another word);
2. θ' ἣ πολλάκις (...that one (demonstrative)/who (relative) many times... etc);
3. θ' ἡ πολλάκις  (...the one many times);
4.  θ' ἢ πολλάκις (...or many times; there are less options for the preceding word in this case, due to Greek sound change rules when words are next to each other in a sentence).

I can't really tell without recovering more context, though some options may be more plausible than others. It really helps if you know the style of the writer/dialect before attempting to fill in the gaps (also, my Greek is rusty, and this is ofc not the kind of problem you face when you're reading a coherent Greek text, so it's not easy at all for a regular classicist).
